---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navbar from '../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../components/seo/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/seo/JsonLd.astro';
import LastUpdated from '../components/seo/LastUpdated.astro';
import ScheduleQuiz from '../components/ScheduleQuiz.astro';
import { getCanonicalUrl } from '../lib/seo/metadata';
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildFAQSchema, buildWebPageSchema } from '../lib/seo/schema';

const title = 'Best Custody Schedule for a Toddler | Examples, Parenting Time & Tips';
const description =
	'Compare the best custody schedules for toddlers, including 2-2-3, 2-2-5-5, and 50/50 arrangements. Includes examples, parenting tips, overnights, and planning tools.';
const canonical = '/best-custody-schedule-for-toddler/';
const canonicalUrl = getCanonicalUrl(canonical);

const breadcrumbs = [
	{ name: 'Home', url: getCanonicalUrl('/') },
	{ name: 'Guides', url: getCanonicalUrl('/blog/') },
	{ name: 'Best Custody Schedule for a Toddler', url: canonicalUrl },
];

const faqItems = [
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a toddler?',
		answer:
			'The best custody schedule for a toddler is usually one that keeps both parent relationships active while protecting routine, sleep, and emotional security. Many toddlers do better with frequent contact and shorter separations than with long blocks away from either parent. A 2-2-3 schedule, a modified 2-2-5-5 schedule, or a custom plan with shorter visits may be worth comparing first when parents live nearby and exchanges are calm. The right answer still depends on the toddler\'s age, temperament, caregiving history, sleep pattern, distance between homes, and how the child settles after exchanges. For toddlers, the decision should start with daily life: naps, meals, bedtime, comfort items, daycare, and whether both parents can follow a predictable routine.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is 50/50 custody good for a toddler?',
		answer:
			'50/50 custody can work for some toddlers, but equal time should not be the only goal. At this age, frequent contact, predictable routines, sleep consistency, and calm exchanges may matter more than a mathematically perfect split. A toddler-friendly 50/50 plan often uses shorter blocks, nearby homes, consistent bedtimes, duplicate supplies, and clear communication between parents. If the toddler has intense distress, disrupted sleep, long travel time, repeated missed naps, or limited familiarity with one home, a modified 60/40 or step-up plan may be more practical while the child grows. Parents should ask whether both homes can handle ordinary care, not just whether the calendar divides time evenly.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How long should a toddler be away from a parent?',
		answer:
			'There is no universal number of nights that works for every toddler. Many toddlers have a limited understanding of time, so two or three days can feel longer than adults expect. Some children handle short overnight blocks well, while others need more gradual steps. Parents often start by looking at the child\'s current caregiving routine, sleep pattern, attachment to each parent, and reaction after exchanges. Long separations may be harder for toddlers than older children, so any plan should be reviewed if it causes ongoing sleep disruption, distress, regression, or repeated difficulty settling. The better question is often: how long can this toddler be away while still sleeping, eating, playing, and reconnecting comfortably?',
	},
	{
		question: 'Are overnight visits good for toddlers?',
		answer:
			'Overnight visits can be good for toddlers when the parent is a familiar caregiver, the home is safe and predictable, and the bedtime routine is realistic. They can help a toddler build everyday connection with both parents, including books, bath, comfort items, night waking, breakfast, and morning care. But overnights can also be challenging if the child is not used to the sleep space, routines are inconsistent, travel is long, or the toddler is already struggling with separation. There is no one-size-fits-all answer. Parents should look at age, relationship history, caregiving involvement, sleep patterns, safety, and how the child behaves after returning.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best for an 18-month-old?',
		answer:
			'An 18-month-old often needs frequent, predictable contact, familiar caregivers, and careful sleep planning. Some families use shorter visits, gradual overnights, or a modified 2-2-3 style rhythm when both parents are already involved and live nearby. The most important details are usually not the schedule label. Parents should focus on feeding, naps, comfort objects, bedtime, illness communication, and whether the child has slept comfortably in both homes. Long separations may be harder at this age because the child has limited language and a limited sense of time. A written step-up plan can help parents expand time without making sudden changes.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best for a 2-year-old?',
		answer:
			'A 2-year-old often benefits from frequent, predictable contact and shorter separations. A 2-2-3 schedule or another short-block plan can be a useful starting point when both parents live close, both homes can manage naps and bedtime, and exchanges are calm. Some families use daytime blocks or shorter overnight blocks before moving toward longer periods. A schedule for a 2-year-old should be simple enough for parents to follow consistently and should protect sleep, meals, daycare routines, comfort items, and communication about illness or missed naps. Tantrums and clinginess can be normal at this age, so parents should watch patterns rather than reacting to one difficult exchange.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best for a 3-year-old?',
		answer:
			'Many 3-year-olds can handle slightly longer blocks than younger toddlers, especially when both homes are familiar and routines are consistent. A 2-2-3 schedule may still work well, while some families begin testing a modified 2-2-5-5, age-appropriate 50/50, or 60/40 plan if preschool logistics require one home to handle more mornings. The plan should still avoid unnecessary complexity. Parents should watch how the child sleeps, separates, returns, and settles after exchanges. Preschool, potty training, early activities, and stronger memory can all change what works. If the child struggles with longer gaps, frequent shorter contact may still be better than moving quickly into full-week blocks.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What if my toddler cries at every exchange?',
		answer:
			'A toddler crying at every exchange does not automatically mean the schedule is wrong, but it is important information. Toddlers may cry because transitions are hard, they are tired, they sense adult tension, they dislike stopping an activity, or they do not understand when they will see the other parent again. Parents should look for patterns: Does crying happen after missed naps, long drives, late exchanges, or conflict? Helpful changes may include a consistent exchange location, a short goodbye routine, a comfort object, calmer adult behavior, and fewer last-minute changes. If distress is extreme, persistent, or paired with major sleep or behavior changes, the schedule may need adjustment.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should nap schedules be included in a parenting plan?',
		answer:
			'Nap schedules are often worth including in a toddler parenting plan, especially when missed naps regularly affect exchanges, bedtime, or behavior. The plan does not need to micromanage every minute, but it can say that parents will share nap timing, missed naps, sleep disruptions, medication, daycare updates, and comfort-item needs. It can also identify whether exchanges should avoid normal nap windows when practical. For toddlers, sleep is part of the custody schedule, not a side issue. A clear nap clause can reduce conflict by making both parents responsible for communicating sleep changes instead of blaming each other after a difficult handoff.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is every other weekend enough for a toddler?',
		answer:
			'Every other weekend may be practical when parents live far apart, one parent has limited availability, or frequent exchanges would create conflict or travel stress. For many toddlers, however, a two-week gap between regular contact with one parent may feel long. If every other weekend is necessary, parents may consider short midweek visits, video calls, consistent routines, holiday time, or a gradual step-up plan if safe and practical. The key question is whether the toddler can maintain a familiar relationship with both parents without creating unnecessary stress. When both parents are nearby and involved, more frequent contact is often worth comparing before defaulting to every other weekend.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Can siblings have different custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Siblings can have different custody schedules in some families, but it should be handled carefully. An older child may manage week-on/week-off or long activity-based blocks, while a toddler may need shorter separations and more routine. Keeping siblings together can provide comfort, but forcing a toddler into an older child\'s schedule can create sleep, transition, or attachment stress. Families sometimes keep the same household exchange days but adjust nap timing, overnight length, calls, or step-up details for the toddler. The goal is to support each child without making the family calendar impossible to follow. If sibling schedules differ, parents should explain the routine simply and avoid making the toddler feel left behind.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do I calculate toddler parenting time?',
		answer:
			'To calculate toddler parenting time, start with where the child sleeps each night, then adjust for holidays, vacations, daycare days, and custom visit blocks. Overnights are the simplest way to estimate custody percentages, but daytime visits can also be important for toddlers, especially during step-up plans. A parenting time calculator or custody percentage calculator can help compare 50/50, 60/40, 70/30, and 80/20 arrangements. The number is useful, but it should be read alongside the child\'s routine, travel time, exchange quality, and ability to stay connected with both parents. A plan with fewer overnights may still include meaningful daytime care if that better fits the child\'s developmental stage.',
	},
];

const toddlerAgeRows = [
