---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>
	<JsonLd slot="head" data={schema} />
	<Navbar />
	<Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs} />
	<main>
		<section class="container-shell py-10 lg:py-14">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Custody schedules by age</p>
				<h1 class="mt-4 max-w-4xl text-5xl font-semibold leading-[0.98] tracking-[-0.055em] text-primary lg:text-6xl">
					Best Custody Schedule for a Toddler
				</h1>
				<LastUpdated />
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-base leading-8 text-secondary lg:grid-cols-[1.2fr_0.8fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4">
						<p>
							A custody schedule that works for a 10-year-old may not work for a toddler. Toddlers are still building language, emotional regulation, sleep rhythms, and a sense of what it means when a parent leaves and comes back.
						</p>
						<p>
							Many toddlers thrive on routine, struggle with long separations, and do not understand time the way older children do. When safe and practical, they often benefit from frequent contact with both parents, but that contact should be planned around naps, bedtime, comfort items, travel time, and calm exchanges.
						</p>
						<p>
							The best toddler custody schedule is not simply the one that looks fairest on a calendar. It is the one the child can live with and the parents can follow consistently.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 text-sm leading-6">
						<p class="font-semibold text-primary">Educational note</p>
						<p class="mt-2 text-secondary">
							This guide is educational and is not legal, medical, or mental health advice. Custody decisions should account for safety, the child\'s needs, existing orders, and qualified local guidance when needed.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="mt-8 flex flex-col gap-3 sm:flex-row">
					<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold sm:w-auto">Use the Custody Schedule Generator</a>
					<a href="#schedule-options" class="btn-secondary inline-flex h-12 w-full items-center justify-center rounded-full px-7 text-sm font-semibold sm:w-auto">Compare toddler schedules</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-8 lg:py-10">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Practical recommendation</p>
				<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Our Practical Recommendation</h2>
				<div class="mt-5 grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[1.1fr_0.9fr]">
					<div class="grid gap-4 text-base leading-8 text-secondary">
						<p>
							For many toddlers, frequent contact is usually more important than perfectly equal time. Long separations can be harder than they are for older children, and a simple repeatable plan often works better than a complicated rotation that changes every few days.
						</p>
						<p>
							A strong starting point is usually a <a href="/2-2-3-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">2-2-3 schedule</a>, a modified <a href="/2-2-5-5-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">2-2-5-5 schedule</a>, an age-appropriate <a href="/50-50-custody-schedule/" class="text-accent underline decoration-line underline-offset-4 hover:text-primary">50/50 custody schedule</a>, or a customized parenting plan that grows with the child.
						</p>
						<p>
							Consistent routines matter more than mathematical fairness. Before choosing a plan, test whether each parent can handle naps, bedtime, comfort items, daycare details, illness, and predictable exchanges.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
						<p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary">Best first comparison</p>
						<ol class="mt-3 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
							<li>1. 2-2-3 for frequent contact.</li>
							<li>2. Modified 2-2-5-5 for older toddlers with strong routines.</li>
							<li>3. Age-appropriate 50/50 only when both homes can support daily care.</li>
							<li>4. Custom plans when work, travel, or attachment needs require flexibility.</li>
						</ol>
						<a href="/custody-schedule-generator/" class="btn-primary mt-5 inline-flex h-11 items-center justify-center rounded-full px-5 text-sm font-semibold">Generate a toddler schedule</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ScheduleQuiz title="Find a Starting Custody Schedule for Your Toddler" ageGroup="toddler" />

		<section class="container-shell py-8 lg:py-10">
			<div class="grid gap-6 lg:grid-cols-[0.8fr_1.2fr]">
				<div>
					<p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-muted">Toddler development</p>
					<h2 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Why Toddler Custody Is Different From School-Age Custody</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">
						Custody planning looks different at age 2 than at age 10 because toddlers depend heavily on adults to create safety, rhythm, and reassurance. A toddler may not understand "next Wednesday," but they often understand whether bedtime feels familiar, whether the exchange is rushed, and whether adults are calm.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
					{[
						['Attachment development', 'Toddlers are still building secure relationships. Frequent, calm, predictable contact can matter more than long blocks.'],
						['Separation anxiety', 'A toddler may cry or cling because transitions are hard, not because one home is bad. Watch patterns over time.'],
						['Language development', 'Many toddlers cannot explain what feels wrong. Behavior, sleep, appetite, and transition reactions become clues.'],
						['Routine dependence', 'Meals, naps, bedtime, daycare, and comfort rituals help toddlers feel oriented when moving between homes.'],
						['Sleep consistency', 'Sleep disruption can make an otherwise reasonable schedule feel unworkable. Bedtime routines should be realistic in both homes.'],
						['Emotional regulation', 'Toddlers borrow calm from adults. Conflict at exchanges can affect the child more than the calendar itself.'],
					].map(([heading, text]) => (
						<article class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5">
							<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-[-0.03em] text-primary">{heading}</h3>
							<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">{text}</p>
						</article>
					))}
