					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">How Separation Anxiety Affects Custody Schedules</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>Separation anxiety can look like crying during exchanges, clinginess, disrupted sleep, more night waking, appetite changes, or regressions around toileting, language, or independence. These reactions can be confusing because a toddler may not be able to explain what feels hard.</p>
						<p>A child crying at an exchange does not automatically mean the schedule is wrong. The child may be tired, overstimulated, reacting to adult tension, or struggling with the moment of goodbye. Look for patterns instead of judging the plan from one difficult handoff.</p>
						<p>Consistency helps. Use predictable routines, calm handoffs, short goodbyes, and simple language. If distress is intense at nearly every exchange, parents may need to shorten separations, adjust exchange timing, or make the routine more predictable.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Comfort Objects, Bedtime Routines, and Consistency</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>Sometimes the issue is not the custody schedule itself, but the difference between homes. A favorite blanket, stuffed animal, bedtime book, cup, sound machine, night light, or sleep phrase can help the toddler recognize that the routine is still familiar.</p>
						<p>Parents should compare mealtime, bath, bedtime, wake-up, daycare, and nap routines. The homes do not need to be identical, but they should not feel like two completely different worlds every few days.</p>
						<p>Duplicate essentials can reduce stress. Keeping pajamas, toothbrushes, diapers or pull-ups, comfort books, snacks, and sleep items in both homes prevents every exchange from feeling like a trip.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
