					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Nap Time and Sleep Considerations</h2>
					<div class="mt-4 grid gap-3 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary">
						<p>Naps are a custody issue for toddlers because missed sleep can affect exchanges, meals, bedtime, and behavior. Parents should share nap times, wake windows, favorite sleep cues, and whether the child still needs a crib, sound machine, pacifier, night light, or special blanket.</p>
						<p>Bedtime routines do not need to be identical, but they should be similar enough that the toddler is not constantly adjusting. A bath, book, song, comfort item, and predictable lights-out time can make both homes feel safer.</p>
						<p>Sleep regressions, illness, travel, and daycare changes can temporarily make a schedule harder. That does not automatically mean the plan is wrong, but it may mean parents need clearer communication and fewer unnecessary schedule changes.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.75rem] p-6">
					<h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">Making Exchanges Easier for Toddlers</h2>
					<ul class="mt-4 grid gap-2 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary">
						<li>Use the same pickup routine when possible.</li>
						<li>Send a favorite toy, blanket, or transition object.</li>
						<li>Keep the exchange location consistent.</li>
						<li>Make handoffs calm, brief, and predictable.</li>
						<li>Avoid adult conflict during pickup and drop-off.</li>
						<li>Use simple words instead of long explanations.</li>
						<li>Keep duplicate essentials in both homes.</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="container-shell py-8 lg:py-10">
			<div class="premium-card rounded-[2rem] p-6 lg:p-8">
				<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What Toddlers Often Remember About Transitions</h2>
				<div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 text-sm leading-7 text-secondary md:grid-cols-2">
					<p>Toddlers may not remember exact schedules. They may not know whether the plan is 2-2-3, 60/40, or every other weekend. But they often remember the emotional tone around transitions: whether adults were calm, whether the goodbye felt rushed, and whether the next routine felt familiar.</p>
					<p>A handoff where parents argue, search for missing shoes, forget the blanket, or give long emotional explanations can feel bigger to a toddler than the actual calendar pattern. A calm exchange at the same location, followed by snack, play, bath, and bedtime, can make the same schedule easier to live with.</p>
					<p>One practical test is to ask: what does the child experience in the first hour after exchange? If the answer is conflict, confusion, and rushing, the schedule may need better structure even if the custody percentage is reasonable.</p>
					<p>This is why toddler custody planning should include routines, not just dates. A toddler experiences the plan through repeated moments: goodbye, car ride, arrival, dinner, bath, comfort object, and sleep.</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

