				<div>
					<h2 class="text-4xl font-semibold leading-[1.05] tracking-[-0.045em] text-primary">What Parents Often Get Wrong About Toddler Custody</h2>
					<p class="mt-4 text-base leading-7 text-secondary">A toddler custody plan can fail because adults focus on the calendar but miss the child\'s daily experience.</p>
				</div>
				<ul class="grid gap-3 text-sm leading-6 text-secondary sm:grid-cols-2">
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Assuming equal time automatically means best, even when the child is not sleeping or settling well.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Changing schedules too often and never giving the toddler a chance to learn the rhythm.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Ignoring nap schedules, then blaming the exchange when the child is overtired.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Using inconsistent bedtimes and expecting the toddler to adapt instantly.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Discussing conflict, blame, or adult logistics in front of the child.</li>
					<li class="soft-card rounded-2xl p-4">Treating comfort items as optional instead of part of the transition plan.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</section>

